english:
  title: Letter to the Great Prince of the Mongol State
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On such and such a month and day, your emissary arrived bearing your esteemed instructions. Through him I learned with great joy that Your Highness, the Great Prince, enjoys boundless health and well-being. Yet in your letter you reproach our humble nation for failing to send maidens and persons versed in Chinese letters and language, nor have we sent the various goods you require. Your reproach is stern and cuts deeply. Upon hearing these words, my heart trembles with fear, and I know not what to do.

    All these people and goods of which you speak—our small nation lacks them entirely. I have already explained twice before why we cannot fulfill such requests, laying bare my sincere heart without concealment. I thought perhaps you might understand and show mercy. Yet still the inquiries continue without end. Is it that my humble sincerity proves too small to move the Great Prince's judgment? Or do you doubt my words as false? If there is any deception in what I say, let Heaven and Earth bear witness. Moreover, our small nation serves the great power with diligence, and we fear we do not show sufficient devotion. How much more so with the gifts required by custom—though we cannot meet your strict demands, would we not wish to send abundance and magnificence to satisfy the great nation's desires?

    Yet the availability of goods depends upon our land and climate. Our nation lies nestled among mountains and valleys, the earth is rocky and barren. Though we produce some things, they are all coarse goods, wholly unfit for your refined use. We send what little we can each year, not from abundance but from sincere affection, merely to maintain the bonds of respect and propriety. Yet you send repeated requests without end. How can our small nation bear this?

    To provide endless demands with finite resources is impossible—I know this well. If we fail to provide, we incur your displeasure, and this contradicts our very hope to lean upon and receive your protection. As for items like azure silk and spun thread—these are not products of our land at all, as I have previously explained. Surely the great nation already understands this. Even for goods our land does produce, their abundance varies with the seasons. How much more so for things our earth does not yield at all?

    Regarding the skilled artisans and craftsmen you request—as stated in my previous letter, our nation has no such masters. Thus we cannot send them. Each failure weighs upon my heart with deep sorrow.

    I humbly reflect that Your Highness, possessed of the dignity of Great Prince and guide to the Son of Heaven's teachings, makes it your duty to bring peace to the four quarters. Toward those from distant lands, I pray you would show forbearance and demonstrate the virtue of cherishing even the small. This is what our humble nation most earnestly hopes.

    Though we cannot provide all the goods you have requested in full measure, we have exhausted our treasury to send what is listed in the attached record. I respectfully entrust these to your returning emissary, asking that at each prefecture and county along the way, the goods be received, inspected, and presented as proof of our effort. May the Great Prince show understanding and not regard our meager offering as a transgression.

    With reverent awe and trembling respect.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This letter was written by Lee Kyu-bo, a leading statesman and scholar of the Goryeo dynasty, to the Mongol Great Prince in response to increasing demands for tribute and resources from the Mongol overlords.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'azure silk and spun thread' (青絲綾走絲) indicates luxury goods that required specialized production capabilities beyond Goryeo's manufacturing capacity.
  - key: ''
    value: The tone of the letter exemplifies the delicate diplomatic language required when a tributary state must respectfully decline or explain its inability to meet a powerful overlord's demands while maintaining the relationship.
